# flight-deals-engine

Background jobs for refreshing flight price datasets and deal candidates for Amiluna.

This repository is intentionally scoped to **flights first**. It should still be designed so the same patterns can later serve a broader trip planner domain (hotels, bundles, planner enrichment, and other market-data refresh flows).

## Current scope

This repo owns the **automation flow** that:

- decides which flight searches should be refreshed
- calls the existing search backend through internal APIs
- normalizes backend responses into internal domain models
- computes refresh outputs such as calendar snapshots and hot-deal candidates
- persists outputs through storage abstractions
- emits logs and metrics around each refresh run

This repo does **not**:

- serve end-user APIs directly
- talk to a third-party flight provider directly
- define database or cache infrastructure
- own frontend rendering

## Why a dedicated repo

The serving backend and the refresh engine have different responsibilities:

- serving backend = synchronous user-facing APIs
- this repo = asynchronous scheduled data production

Keeping them separate makes it easier to:

- evolve scheduling logic independently
- run local refresh jobs safely
- introduce new refresh strategies without touching serving code
- reuse refresh outputs for web, Telegram, Instagram, and later planner flows

## Initial architecture

```text
EventBridge Schedule
    -> Lambda handler
        -> Job runner
            -> Search planner
                -> Existing search backend adapter
                    -> Normalizer
                        -> Storage adapter(s)
                            -> future DB/cache implementation in infra repo
```

## Phase 1 principles

- Flights only
- Lambda runtime
- No direct provider integration here
- Existing search backend is the system of record for search execution
- No database/cache Terraform in this repo
- Storage is represented by interfaces and placeholder adapters only
- Build for local execution and testability from day one

